So I think we should update the fragment (https://figgy.princeton.edu/catalog/29a70eaa-5e27-4501-9932-5321c383fc61) to have a new ARK, and then it will stop conflicting with the other object.

pomegranate.title: Failed to index error should reference noid instead of id
5k+ Western Americana (WC064) items not indexing in DPUL collection

comments.body: The error queue definitely does not have this many items in it, and the sample items given are not in the queue (not in any of the queues). So it doesn't look like this is a rabbitmq issue. I'll update the description with the links.

Update: For resources with finding aid source_metadata_ids, figgy's jsonld has a nested collection object. when indexing into pomegranate, solr thinks this is a child document, which it's not set up to handle. This appears to be the source of the problem here. Still need to do some more analysis on what jsonld should look like.

The jsonld also has the `memberOf` field, so I think just removing the `member_of_collection_ids` field should be fine.

princeton_ansible.title: Redis can't set maximum open files to 10032 because of OS error: Operation not permitted.

comments.body:
https://coderwall.com/p/j5osrg/when-redis-can-t-set-maximum-open-files

Solution

Actually, Redis's init script will check if a ULIMIT variable is set and call ulimit -n $ULIMIT before starting the Redis instance.
In order to set the ULIMIT var, simply open up /etc/defaults/redis-server and uncomment the ULIMIT=65536. Restart your Redis and it will set the ulimit for your redis user correctly.

Hope this helps someone

(PS Only tested on Ubuntu)
